{{Quote|Robin Gurland had me read Shelagh Fraser's lines during my audition. Leading up to that, I spent a lot of time watching her performance and getting a sense for how she held herself and how she spoke. I didn't want to make it exactly like her because this was years earlier in the story and I wanted to show the younger, more innocent side of Beru.|Bonnie Maree Piesse|<ref name="Insider 136">{{InsiderCite|136|In Their Own Words: The Cast on the Making of Episode II}}</ref>}}
'''Bonnie Maree Piesse''' (born [[August 10]], [[1983]]) is an actress and singer/songwriter who played [[Beru Whitesun Lars]] in both [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Attack of the Clones'']] and [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith|''Revenge of the Sith'']]. She reprised her role in the television series ''[[Star Wars: Obi-Wan Kenobi]]'', as Beru Whitesun Lars.

==Biography==
===The prequel trilogy===
Bonnie Maree Piesse was born on [[August 10]], [[1983]].<ref name="SWYT Life Day" /> At the age of 16, she got a call from [[Robin Gurland]], the casting director for [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Attack of the Clones'']], who wanted to audition her for a role in the movie. She eventually got the part of [[Beru Whitesun Lars|Beru Lars]],<ref name="OffWeb">{{WebCite|url=https://www.bonniepiesse.com|text=Bonnie Piesse|archivedate=20190814015638}}</ref> previously portrayed by [[Shelagh Fraser]] in [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']].<ref name="Episode IV">{{Film|IV}}</ref> On [[July 7]], [[2000]], [[StarWars.com]] announced that Piesse would be playing the role of a younger Beru in ''Attack of the Clones''.<ref name="Casting">{{SWArchive|url=episode-ii/bts/production/news20000707.html|text=Casting Update: More Local Talent}}</ref> Piesse approached Beru as being a little shy, the idea being that it was the introduction of [[Luke Skywalker]] into her life that matured her.<ref name="Insider3">{{InsiderCite|58|Bonnie Piesse: Micro Beru}}</ref> In [[September]], 2000, Piesse and the crew were filming the [[Tatooine]] scenes in [[Tunisia]].<ref name="Mythmaking: Behind the Scenes of Attack of the Clones">''[[Mythmaking: Behind the Scenes of Attack of the Clones]]''</ref>

Piesse reprised her role as Beru in the [[2005]] film [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith|''Star Wars'': Episode III ''Revenge of the Sith'']].<ref name="Episode III">{{Film|III}}</ref> Director [[George Lucas]] filmed part of a scene for the film in which a stand-in actor playing [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]] delivers baby Luke to [[Owen Lars]], played by [[Joel Edgerton]]. During the Episode III shoot in September, [[2003]], Lucas filmed [[Ewan McGregor]] handing the baby to Piesse, with Owen being played by a stand-in&mdash;Edgerton would be shot and added in almost a year later. Lucas made this change because he "felt it would be better if Luke were handed over to a woman."<ref name="The Making of Star Wars Revenge of the Sith">''[[The Making of Star Wars Revenge of the Sith]]''</ref> In an interview, Piesse admitted that her role in ''[[Star Wars]]'' had been "a huge help in my career."<ref name="Backstage">{{WebCite|url=https://www.backstage.com/magazine/article/bonnie-piesse-got-part-59541|text=Bonnie Piesse&hellip; Got the Part|author=Lehman, Daniel|date=2011-04-06|archivedate=20200805200754}}</ref>

===''Obi-Wan Kenobi'' television series===
{{Quote|So some roles are an easier fit than others. And this one just fits so easily that I didn't feel I had to try too hard to embody her. The main way to prepare was just&mdash;after everything I'd been through, I was still recovering from PTSD. So I did a lot to heal and nourish myself and strengthen myself to make sure that I had all the energy that I needed to be on set. So it was more supporting myself.|Bonnie Piesse discussing playing Beru Lars in ''Obi-Wan Kenobi''|<ref name="Bonnie Piesse interview">{{WebCite|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/movies-tv/a40084975/bonnie-piesse-nxivm-star-wars-obi-wan-kenobi|text=Bonnie Piesse Escaped The Cult NXIVM. Now, She's Back In The Star Wars Universe.|author=Pope-Puckett, Lauren|date=2022-05-24|work=[[Wikipedia:Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|archivedate=20220524141703}}</ref>}}
Piesse loved watching what had been done with the new ''Star Wars'' and she loved [[Star Wars: Episode VII The Force Awakens|''Star Wars'': Episode VII ''The Force Awakens'']]. After spending many years meeting fans and learning what ''Star Wars'' means to people, Piesse started to appreciate ''Star Wars'' and she learned more about the franchise. Piesse has said ''Star Wars'' means much more to her than it did before and she "kind of became a fan in a whole new way."<ref name="Bonnie Piesse interview" />

[[File:LarsFamilyBTS.png|thumb|right|180px|Bonnie Piesse, Joel Edgerton, and [[Grant Feely]] on the [[Lars homestead|Lars Homestead]] set]]
After escaping from the cult [[Wikipedia:NXIVM|NXIVM]], Piesse had not been trying to pursue acting and was processing her [[Wikipedia:Post-traumatic stress disorder|PTSD]] from the experience. She did not return to [[Wikipedia:Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] until she received a message from [[Deborah Chow]], the director of the ''[[Star Wars: Obi-Wan Kenobi]]'' television series. When Piesse first received Chow's message to chat, she did not recognize it as having to do with work. She ignored the message for almost a week until realizing the message was for casting. Piesse then joined a call from [[Wikipedia:Portugal|Portugal]], and Chow convinced her to return to the role of Beru Lars.<ref name="Bonnie Piesse interview" /> Chow was excited to bring Edgerton and Piesse back to play Owen and Beru Lars, respectively, and she said their return was part of what made the series special.<ref name="17 year">{{WebCite|url=https://ew.com/tv/obi-wan-kenobi-ewan-mcgregor-hayden-christensen-cover-story|text=Inside the 17-year journey to reunite Ewan McGregor and Hayden Christensen for ''Obi-Wan Kenobi''|author=Ross, Dalton|date=2022-03-10|work=''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''|archivedate=20220310151626}}</ref> Piesse and Edgerton were excited to see each other again. She didn't feel pressured because it felt like everyone wanted to be there.<ref name="Return">''[[Obi-Wan Kenobi: A Jedi's Return]]''</ref>

Piesse got to embody Lars in a different way, and her portrayal was a middle space between Lars starting to be a mother and Shelagh Fraser's portrayal in the [[original trilogy]]. Piesse felt like she did not need to try too hard to embody Lars because it was a character that "just fits so easily." Piesse prepared by healing, nourishing, and strengthening herself to have all the energy she needed to be on set.<ref name="Bonnie Piesse interview" /> On [[March 29]], [[2021]], [[Lucasfilm]] confirmed Piesse as a cast member of the live-action [[Disney+]] television series ''Obi-Wan Kenobi''.<ref name="SW">{{SW|url=news/obi-wan-kenobi-series-cast|text=''Obi-Wan Kenobi'' Series to Begin Production in April, Cast Revealed}}</ref> Piesse has said she would like to continue acting in a second season or an adjacent film for ''Obi-Wan Kenobi''.<ref name="Bonnie Piesse interview" />

